# Chart visual readability rules

Apply when editing chart renderers, chart theme tokens, or chart tab wrappers.

1. **Layered backgrounds are mandatory**: define and use separate semantic tokens for chart figure/page background and plot-area background.
2. **Centralized base style**: baseline Matplotlib styling (facecolor, grid, spine, ticks, axis-label color) must be applied by shared entrypoint (`app/charts/base_chart.py`), not duplicated per chart.
3. **Token-first colors**: use semantic chart tokens for lines, bars, limits, anomalies, and annotations; avoid one-off hard-coded colors except documented per-feature palette constants.
4. **Density readability**: density-like charts (hexbin/heatmap) must preserve visibility in sparse regions and keep colorbar text readable.
5. **Meaning-safe visual edits**: visual-only refactors must not alter statistical formulas, thresholds, metadata semantics, or interpretation text.
6. **Regression coverage required**: chart visual behavior changes should include or update tests for style application and chart readability signals (for example colorbar/annotations).
